Date: Fri, 12 Jan 2001 10:29:04 +0100
From: Francois Moutou <f.moutou@afssa.fr>

Here is a comment about moderator MHJ's remark on otter diet at the end of
the information on rabies in otter (which is not the first case in North
America). Even if the Eurasian otter (_Lutra lutra_) is a little different
from the North American otter (_Lutra canadensis_), even at the generic
[genetic? level, they do share some common habits.
For instance, from our experience here, even if their diet is mostly fish,
they do eat other prey when available, like crayfish, frogs when they meet
for frying [sic or even some small water mammals. A young muskrat
(introduced in Europe) could be caught and eaten. However, in this case,
the origin of the disease is most probably a carnivore as rodents are [an
epidemiological dead end.
--
Francois Moutou
<f.moutou@afssa.fr>
