[2
Date: Fri 12 Jan 2001 09:18:38 -0500
From: Chuck Trimarchi <trimarch@wadsworth.org>

This is not unprecedented. We have had 2 laboratory-confirmed rabid river
otters (_Lutra canadensis_) in New York State since raccoon rabies spread
into the state in 1991. Spill-over of the raccoon rabies variant into
non-rabies vector, wild mammalian species has been quite common. In New
York we have had confirmed cases also in a black bear, bobcats, coyotes,
whitetail deer, a fisher, a muskrat, opossum, and woodchucks, as well as
the otters. Spill-over into domesticated species during the period has
included, in addition to cats and dogs, a camel, cattle, Sika deer,
ferrets, goats, horses, swine, domestic rabbits, and sheep.
--
Chuck Trimarchi
<trimarch@wadsworth.org>
