[4
Date: Fri 12 Jan 2001 12:14:49 -0600
From: Rickard S. Toomey, III <toomey@museum.state.il.us>

I would agree that a rabid otter is unusual, but not overly so. John W.
Krebs and others (1998) report 5 rabid otters for 1997 in the United States.
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/rabies/professional/Surveillance97/surv97.htm>
One was reported in 1998 (Krebs and others 1999) in the US.
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/rabies/professional/Surveillance98/Surv98.htm>
Rabid otters have also been found in Canada. One apparently attacked a
child in northern Quebec in 1996.
<http://www.gov.nf.ca/agric/her&rab/rabqueb.htm>
On a separate point, river otters do occasionally prey on muskrats
(Ceballos-G. 1999). However, I would certainly agree that eating a rabid
muskrat is very unlikely to be the source of the rabies in the
otter. Muskrats show up with rabies even less often than otters (although
even they do sometimes show up rabid). An encounter with a rabid raccoon
would be much more likely.
(non-online) Reference cited
Cegallos-G, G., 1999, Northern river otter, _Lontra canadensis_, in (D.E.
Wilson and S. Ruff, eds.) The Smithsonian Book of North American Mammals.
Washington, DC: Smithsonian Institution Press. p. 179-180.
--
Rickard S. Toomey, III, Ph.D.
Illinois State Museum, Illinois Dept. of Natural Resources
Springfield, Illinois, USA
<toomey@museum.state.il.us>
